ter took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.','Lava and Neora Valley 2015','','inherit','closed','closed','','96-revision-v1','','','2016-12-29 21:41:55','2016-12-29 16:11:55','',96,'http://amitayu.com/96-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(98,1,'2016-12-29 21:42:38','2016-12-29 16:12:38','Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry\'s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.','Mahabaleshwar 2015','','publish','open','open','','mahabaleshwar-2015','','','2016-12-29 21:42:38','2016-12-29 16:12:38','',0,'http://amitayu.com/?p=98',0,'post','',0),(99,1,'2016-12-29 21:42:38','2016-12-29 16:12:38','Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry\'s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.','Mahabaleshwar 2015','','inherit','closed','closed','','98-revision-v1','','','2016-12-29 21:42:38','2016-12-29 16:12:38','',98,'http://amitayu.com/98-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(100,1,'2016-12-29 21:43:15','2016-12-29 16:13:15','July 2<sup>nd</sup> marked the beginning of my monsoon trips in 2015. A friend of ours, my wife and I started from Pune at midnight in a rental car and reached Amboli in about 8 hours. We took the Belgaum route to reach Amboli, 70 kms from Belgaum. Amboli is known as the Cherrapunji of Maharashtra because it receives a whopping 23 feet of average rainfall per year. It is a quaint hill station in the south of Maharashtra, barely 100kms from Goa.\r\n\r\nI had arranged for our stay in Whistling Woods, the resort owned by Hemant Ogale, the renowned butterfly enthusiast. I was delighted to see the familiar face of Shubham Alave, our local guide.\r\n\r\nAt 5pm we walked towards a dilapidated fort which was about 1 km from our resort. As soon as we came upon the old, moss-covered broken building, we caught hold of a Malabar whistling thrush crossing our way. The building did not hold too many species but we were rewarded with the sightings of two Brooke\'s geckos and a whip scorpion. The light was going down by then and we were expecting the frogs and toads to get busy.\r\n\r\nAs it got darker, the prominent typewriters became active. Bombay bush frogs and Amboli bush frogs make sounds similar to a type-writer, that is why they are nicknamed as typewriter frogs.\r\n\r\nAmidst the tic tic tic tic of the bush frogs, there was a distinct call. Nyctibatrachus petraeus! All three frogs are endemic to Western Ghats. We went off trail and entered the mud and thickets by the side of the road. Soon we came across an Amboli bush frog and a Bombay bush frog, hardly a foot apart from each other. Both males were croaking, their vocal sacs fully distended. A male Nyctibatrachus was immersed in a mud puddle. Its orange nose-tip was clearly visible on top of its wrinkled, glistening skin. And its iris, spread in a perfect square in the flash light.\r\n\r\nAs soon as we backed up on the road, we realized that thick mist had descended and visibility was very low, typical weather of Amboli during monsoons. Upon reaching Whistling Woods, we were led to a special spot at the back of the resort. To our amazement, there were countless Malabar gliding frogs there. Few of them were mating, few croaking and few simply chilling out. Several foam nests were visible above a lotus tank. Hyper active tadpoles swam up and down the length of the tank. The evening trail had turned extremely fruitful, so my group was very excited about the night trail.\r\n\r\nDinner was quickly served. It consisted of fish fries, fish gravy, rice and dry prawns. Being a non-fish-eating Bengali does not have any perks. I had to be content with <em>solkadi</em> and rice, a strange combination while my wife gorged on fish fries.\r\n\r\nAt 10pm, we all were ready for the night trail. Our destination was a particular garden created by the forest department. While walking towards the garden we came upon a banded gecko, a <em>ramanella marmorata </em>and an Amboli toad. As soon as we reached the garden we spotted a few Malabar gliding frogs. The trail had just started when it began pouring cats and dogs. The raincoats and gumboots were no match to the heavy downpour. We had to take shelter under a rickety tin shed on the path. Shubham was not affected much by the rain. Just as the rain stopped, we heard his call. We ran towards him with our flashlights. He pointed to a dead branch with his torch and there we saw the season\'s first Malabar pit viper, a juvenile light-green morph. The trail was successful.\r\n\r\nThe next day after breakfast, we ventured to the plateau of Amboli. The plateau consisted of laterite rocks and basket \'karvi\' shrubs. The weather kept on changing every few seconds. It was sunny one moment, misty and rainy the other. We were surprised to find innumerable Amboli toads on the plateau. I was almost scared that I would step on a few of them. Amboli toads are critically endangered. We were lucky to spot more than a thousand of them. We spotted an adult black scorpion sitting patiently on one of the rocks. Unfortunately, as soon as we started clicking, it decided to hide behind the rocks. How much ever we tried to turn the rocks and get a look at it, it hid further, almost like a hamster on a wheel.\r\n\r\nWe decided to leave the scorpion alone and tread further towards a temple on the plateau. I turned almost every stone in the vicinity and was rewarded with the most lucrative sighting of the season. An olive forest snake!!! I was in search of this snake for quite some time. I could not have been happier. We clicked the snake ravenously and finally let it go after a while. A juvenile checkered-keelback, a pink crab and a couple of eels and multiple green vine snakes were spotted. This was proving to be one of the most successful trips to the Eco Hot-spot in the Sahyadri Hills.\r\n\r\nAfter lunch and a short nap, we went out for the evening trail. We went back to the plateau, a different spot this time. In almost every puddle, there were miniature and medium sized eels. Rocks were carefully upturned and returned back to their respective positions. Several forest scorpions with juveniles on their backs were found. A lone Amboli toad was found along with a burrowing frog. But the main attraction of the trail was a caecilian ichthyophis. We got a few clean shots of the wonderful creature. And then it was time for return. Returning back to the resort, we decided to check the backyard for more activity. Imagine the surprise when I suddenly spotted a Malabar pit viper slowly inching towards one of the gliding frogs, who was croaking mightily on a bush. We all were waiting eagerly to capture one of the rarest moments in camera. But even after waiting for several hours, our luck did not strike the right chord. We geared up again after dinner and started the night trail at 10pm.\r\n\r\nThe forest was dense on either sides of the unending tar road. Mist covered the end of the road making visibility very poor. The light from our torches tried to penetrate through the mist creating a smoky effect. We walked in perfect silence, breaking it only when something was spotted.\r\n\r\nNo sooner had we started the trail that we came upon a super agile Beddome\'s cat snake (Boiga trigonata). A few feet ahead, we came upon a Malabar pit viper, a dark green morph. We got a total of seven Malabar pit vipers that night. After a point we almost stopped clicking them. There were plenty of Nyctis too. Some males were seen guarding the eggs and croaking simultaneously. Bull frogs were not spotted but several calls were heard. Huge numbers of Skittering frogs were croaking wildly in a stagnant pool. To take a break during the trail, we sat down in the middle of the road and switched off our lights. Only then, a bioluminescent plant was seen glowing by the side of the road. That particular trail had a surreal effect on all of us.\r\n\r\nIt was almost 1 am when we decided to return back. A fully grown Prasad\'s gecko and a Sahyadri forest rat were also spotted on our walk back.\r\n\r\nThe next morning was the last day of our stay in Amboli. Early in the morning, we went out for visiting the main waterfall. By the time we reached, it was already over-crowded with holiday makers. After spending very little time at the spot, we left for Hiranyakeshwar temple, an ancient Shiva temple at the cave which is the source of the Hiranyakeshi river. The trip also gave us the opportunity to spot plenty of puff-throated babblers and a couple of white-bellied blue flycatchers.\r\n\r\nWe bade farewell to Shubham, Hemant and the rest of the staff at the resort. It was a trip we all would remember because the sighting was far better than usual. After lunch, we left for our respective desti