road conditions would have taken us to our destination in half the time. But the last 30kms to Miao was a roller coaster ride and not for the faint-hearted and the weak-stomached.\r\nOur local contact was Mr. Phupla Singhpo. He had already arranged for the <strong>innerline</strong> <strong>permit</strong> for us, so we did not have to spend much time at <strong>Namchik</strong> checkpost while entering Arunachal Pradesh. We stayed at the resort of Mr. Singhpo that night at Miao.\r\nI had a quick introduction with Biki and Moshang, our guides, as we set out towards Namdapha in the morning. We reached the entrance of Namdapha Forest Reserve. We had to pay for our camera equipments at the entrance and give the forest officials a few details of our stay in the forest. After a few minutes, we officially entered Namdapha, the mother of all forests.\r\nEnormous chestnut tiger butterflies were idly fluttering around the dense undergrowth of the forest. There are around 500 species of butterflies in <strong>Namdapha</strong>. We entered the Noa-Dihing Valley en route to <strong>Deban</strong>. I spotted our first Plumbeous Water <strong>Redstart</strong> and White-capped Redstart while crossing a clear stream of flowing water. These two birds would be our constant companion along the streams and rivers that we would come across for the next 5 days. We also spotted a Slaty-backed Forktail, common kingfisher, Indian roller, long-tailed shrikes and other common birds.\r\nDeban is the point from where we were about to start the trek on foot. Luckily the forest authorities provided an elephant for us. We were delighted to know that Lokkhi (Laxmi) and her young daughter Diwani would be our companions for the entire journey. All our supplies and personal belongings were bundled up on Lokkhis back.\r\nAs the crew was preparing packed lunch boxes for us and getting ready for the trek, I quickly took a tour around the place. In no time I spotted a <strong>Malayan giant squirrel</strong> jumping along the branches of tall trees. It was dark brown in colour, unlike its Malabar counterpart. Orange yellow tip butterflies were omni present. Yellow-bellied <strong>fantail</strong> would go round and round in loops until I stopped following its dizzying trail of flight. The mighty <strong>Sultan tit</strong> and a few warblers were also spotted.\r\n<strong> Day 1</strong>\r\nThe beginning of our trek had us walk along <strong>Noa Dihing</strong> River. We spotted brown dippers and little forktails and pied king fisher.\r\nWe had lunch along the side of the river after a couple of hours of trekking. After lunch we drank the water from the river. I have a habit of drinking water from flowing streams and rivers whenever out in the wild. But that particular stream-water tasted exceptionally sweet and heavenly.\r\nSoon after, we entered the dense forests of Namdapha. We came upon a particular coral tree which had almost ten different species of birds at the same time. Our frenzied clicks started. We had to move on from the tree when our guides informed us that it was necessary to reach the campsite on time.\r\nThe sun had begun to set at about 4 pm. It was the first day of trek and our bodies were tired after a mere 7kms but our spirits were indomitable. After a while we reached <strong>Happy Valley</strong>, our first camp site in Namdapha. The camp was set up just beside the Noa-Dihing river. We were served steaming hot tea and biscuits while we sat by the gushing river.\r\nDinner consisted of fried beans, dal, egg curry, roti and rice. The heavy meal made us sleepy and we retired for the night early.\r\n<strong> Day 2</strong>\r\nThe second day started on a very exciting note. From early on in the morning, we could hear loud hoops of <strong>Hoolock gibbons</strong> near our camp site. A pair was spotted climbing a distant tree. It was located so far away that only their movements made us spot them.\r\nWe set out for an 11km trek to <strong>Hornbill Point</strong> shortly after breakfast. On our way, we spotted the sultan tits, scarlet minivets, grey-headed canary flycatcher and asian fairy bluebird. Photography was extremely difficult because light hardly reached the mossy floors of the forest penetrating thick canopy of the tall trees. Most of the journey was pure and simple bird watching.\r\nWe reached Hornbill Point at about 3pm. It was completely different from the Happy Valley campsite. This one was set up on a clearing in the middle of the forest. The stream running by its side was a feebly flowing water body. Time flew by and we were in the middle of an intense discussion when Biki came running to us with a smile and whispered, <strong>Flying squirrel</strong>!\r\nWe sprang up, grabbed our torches and cameras. The flying squirrel was silently feeding on the tree beside our camp.\r\nBack at the camp, we had a sumptuous dinner of rice, dal, cabbage, roti and roasted papad. All meals were a feast in the middle of the jungle and our cook and helpers ensured the best for us. We retired for the night soon after dinner.\r\n<strong> Day 3</strong>\r\nNext morning, our guides took us to the woods with the sole purpose of justifying the name of the campsite, Hornbill Point! Besides spotting a <strong>Rufous-necked Hornbill</strong> pair, as an added bonus we got to see rusty-fronted <strong>barwing</strong>, ashy bulbul, <strong>white-throated bulbul</strong>, asian fairy bluebird, blue-throated barbet and <strong>white-hooded babbler</strong>.\r\nAfter breakfast, we packed up and were about to leave when we heard a commotion up in the trees. A <strong>hoary bellied squirrel</strong>!! Everybody gathered around to click the squirrel when something bright attracted my attention. And then I saw it, a male red-headed <strong>Trogon</strong>, the Santa claus of Northeast! It swooped down from a tree and flew into the dense jungle. Though sighted for just 2 to 3 seconds, its vivid red colour could only make us smile. The day had started on an overwhelming note. I was excited to see what else it held for us.\r\nWe set out for our next destination, <strong>Ranijheel</strong>, which was about 7kms from Hornbill Point. We decided that we would have a slow-paced trek that day.\r\nMultiple flocks of whiskered and black-chinned yuhinas and rusty-fronted barwings were spotted. We reached a bend, where a log had fallen across the trail. We decided to catch our breath for a few mintues at that place. As we sat on the fallen log, craning our necks high up to look for birds, we heard distinct squealing from the nearby trees. Our guides got up to their feet. Biki told me that it could be a marten. Yellow-throated martens are common in those areas. The squealing continued. After several minutes of waiting silently, we got to see the animals causing the commotion. Two Malayan giant squirrels were chasing each other on high branches. The rest of our journey was hot and tiring. But we could spot a small <strong>Niltava</strong>, plenty of scarlet minivets, black-eared <strong>shrike-babbler</strong> and <strong>black-headed</strong> shrike-babbler.\r\nDuring lunch, we came to know that we were just about 1.5 kms away from our destination. But the last part of the trek was particularly difficult because we were continuously supposed to climb uphill till Ranijheel.\r\nIt was indeed a tough climb. The slopes were steep and our unaccustomed bodies needed rest every 5 minutes. We were informed that about a few years back, Ranijheel was a \'jheel\' (a lake) with plenty of water. All that was left of the lake now was an almost dried-up swamp. As soon as we reached the campsite, we dropped our bags and went on an inspection of the dead lake. There was not much activity of birds.\r\nAt night while we had dinner, it was decided that the next day, the elephants and half of the crew will not be accompanying us to Firmbase, our final destination. The main reason behind the decision was that there was a bamboo thicket en route to our final destination and the elephants would find it extremely difficult to cross.\r\n<strong>Day 4</strong>\r\nWe woke up early on Day 4. The previous evening at Ranijheel was unfruitful, so we just had the morning to make up for it. Without having breakfast, we set out on leech-infested path. The new birds identified in that area were red-billed scimitar babbler and imperial pigeons. Moshang was looking up at a tall tree by the side of the trail and suddenly he started jumping with excitement. He pointed at the tree and squealed like a mad man. It was a green <strong>Cochoa</strong>, one of the <strong>rarest</strong> birds of Namdapha!!! Not one or two but atleast five of them! Though very widely distributed in the Eastern Himalayas and parts of SE Asia, this species is described as rare or rarely seen. I got an okayish shot of the stunning bird! Spotting a green Cochoa required immense luck. I could not be happier.\r\nWhile returning back to the camp, my wife and I were trailing behind the group. We spotted a few silver-eared tesias flurrying underneath the bushes. Capturing the super shy birds in camera was next to impossible. I looked up from the bushes to scan the tall trees when my glance suddenly fixated upon a couple of birds silently hopping on the branch above us. At first I could not identify the elegant creatures. But when I saw its unmistakable eye-patch, I realized that it was a pair of <strong>Beautiful Sibia</strong>!\r\nSoon after breakfast, we left for Firmbase. It was an 11km trek again. This trek was very different from the others. Almost 5kms of the trek was downhill on loose sandy terrain. Our feet had to be in total control and our bodies in sync. Luckily, none of us lost control while climbing down the steep, unsteady slopes. And the best part was that we reached our destination in only 3 hours, just in time for lunch. Lunch felt like a huge reward for our meagre achievement. Each of our lunch boxes had six puris with deep fried potatoes!!\r\n<strong>Firmbase</strong> was different from the other camps. Instead of tents, we were provided a spacious wooden hut for our halt. The hut belonged to the forest officials, who were posted there to curb poaching and illegal deforestation. After dropping off our luggage at the hut, we set out for the mighty Namdapha river, which was at about a kilometre from the camp.\r\nThe Namdapha river took our breath away. It boomed, glittered and shimmered from all angles.\r\nBiki\'s pointed to the sky and there was a <strong>white-bellied heron</strong> flying past our heads! The purpose of coming to Firm Base was served. It is estimated that there are only 250 white-bellied herons left in the world and only about 50 left in India. The confluence of Noa-Dihing and Namdapha rivers in the Namdapha Tiger Reserve supports a few individuals of white-bellied heron by providing them with freshwater fish.\r\nAfter sunset, we returned to the camp. A gorgeous fire was awaiting us along with steaming hot cups of tea. The night was full of underlying melancholy about the fact that the next day we had to embark upon our return journey.\r\n<strong> Day 5</strong>\r\nNext morning, we revisited Namdapha river. Though not white-bellied herons, we spotted plenty of <strong>black-necked storks</strong>, river lapwings and redstarts.\r\nAfter a hearty breakfast of maggi and tea, we set out to cover the periphery of the camp. We came upon a tree which was filled with pin-tailed and wedge-tailed green pigeons. There might have been atleast a hundred of them. We could spot them from a distance of 300 metres but as soon as we got closer, we lost them completely. So good was their camouflage. Other sightings included common rosefinch, streaked spiderhunter, chestnut tailed starling, fulvous-breasted woodpecker and red-whiskered bulbuls (without red whiskers). After the morning birding expedition came to an end, we bade farewell to the forest officials, to the birds, to the beautiful river. There could never have been a more fitting final destination than Firmbase.\r\nWe had a long return journey all the way back to Hornbill camp. As soon as the return began, we spotted a collared owlet. After getting numerous clicks of the little wonder, we went ahead. I also spotted <strong>red-billed scimitar babbler</strong> and <strong>lesser rufous-headed parrotbill</strong> at a thicket by the trail.\r\nAfter lunch at Renijheel, we continued walking towards Hornbill. It was hot and humid but the monotony was broken when a flock of wreathed hornbills flew over our heads.\r\nWe wanted to visit <strong>Bulbulia</strong>, which was located a couple of kilometers before Hornbill Point. It was already getting darker, so we sped up a bit. Bulbulia was famous for its <strong>sulphur-methane</strong> spring. We had immense fun lighting the bubbling methane gas from the spring. We were lucky to spot a pair of barred cuckoo doves there. Unfortunately we did not have much time to spend at the spot since we had to be at the Hornbill camp before it got too dark.\r\nThere was a distinct call of a couple of hornbills throughout the trail from Bulbulia to Hornbill Point. The only problem was that we could not locate the birds. At one point I could take it no longer. So, as my friends waited on the trail, I ventured off-track into the forest. There was a tall tree with white bark at the fringe of the forest. The calls grew louder at this point. I looked up and to my extreme satisfaction, could spot a pair of Austen\'s Brown Hornbills right up at the tree.\r\nWe were almost at the camp, when we decided to stop at the Hornbill Point. Even though it was almost dark, this particular patch provided us with new sightings. A female <strong>sapphire</strong> flycatcher, white-bellied <strong>erpornis</strong> and <strong>white-hooded</strong> babbler were spotted among the usuals.\r\nFinally we reached Hornbill camp and were welcomed with fried finger chips, hot cups of tea and a crackling fire.\r\n<strong> Day 6</strong>\r\nIt was my last day in Namdapha. We began our long trek back to Deban at about 9am in the morning. The forest was damp from previous night\'s rainfall and the sky was overcast. Although the conditions were unfavorable, we managed to spot a female red-headed trogon and white-browed fantail. A flock of <strong>Brown hornbills</strong> were in transit.\r\nMoshang spotted a white-browed <strong>Piculet</strong> and motioned us to get a closer look at a particular branch. But before our eyes could catch a glimpse of the cute little bird, it flew away.\r\nAfter lunch, we trekked on and reached the Noa-Dihing river belt in record time . A crested serpent eagle was majestically sitting on a nearby tree, giving us ample photo opportunity. We had reached before time, so we sat on the river bank for long, dipped our feet and had our last drink. We eventually crossed the Noa-Dihing river. The water level had risen considerably because of heavy rains the night before.\r\nWe reached Deban at about 2pm. It marked the end of our trek to Namdapha. After relaxing for almost an hour, we bade good bye to the adorable elephants, the mahouts and one of our guides, Moshang. The rest of the crew accompanied us till the resort in Miao. We reached Miao after dark.\r\nI got up early the next morning. We still had a couple of hours before we start our journey towards Dibrugarh airport. I spent my last few hours in Miao walking barefoot on the grass of the forest resort, the wind from the nearby stream blew my hair and the fragrance of wild untouched nature, invaded my nostrils. I knew that I will be going back with my heart full of new hopes and new dreams. Namdapha had humbled me in all ways possible.','Namdapha National Park','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2017-01-18 21:42:05','2017-01-18 16:12:05','',92,'http://amitayu.com/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(247,1,'2017-01-18 21:43:26','2017-01-18 16:13:26','<strong>Ganeshgudi</strong> trip was planned on the spur of a moment. I happened to browse through the website of <strong>Old Magazine House</strong> (OMH) one fine evening and went through the tariff and the reservation page (it was purely coincidental). The availability of a cottage was making me very uncomfortable but convincing the wife to take a leave at such a short notice seemed a herculean task. Luckily God has bestowed us with sick leaves. So after a few days, on the 14th of March, 2014, in the wee hours of the morning, we boarded a train from Pune.\r\n<img class=\"img-responsive wp-image-10 size-large alignleft\" src=\"http://amitayu.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Green_Vine_Snake-1024x509.jpg\" width=\"720\" height=\"358\">\r\n\r\n<strong>How to reach</strong> - We reached Londa, which is the nearest railway station from Ganeshgudi, at about 10.30 am. Old Magazine House was about 30kms from Londa. You can either take a cab all the way to the destination or take a bus from Ramnagar. We took an auto rickshaw to Ramnagar bus stop, which is around 6 to 7kms from Londa station. From there we took a bus to Ganeshgudi, which is located 25km from Dandeli on Londa to Dandeli road.\r\n\r\n<strong>Stay</strong> - The resort is located near Supa dam which offers a picturesque view. You can refer this link- <a href=\"http://www.junglelodges.com/old-magazine-house/\">http://www.junglelodges.com/old-magazine-house/</a> .We reached there at around 12 noon. The bus dropped us at a turning, almost a kilometer from Supa dam. The best landmark is the old wooden board which read - The Old Magazine House. As we were walking towards the resort in the sweltering heat, we were welcomed by a <strong>Great Indian Hornbill</strong> whooshing past our heads. I could not retrieve my camera gear on time, which was packed away in the backpack.\r\nWe checked in and were awestruck by the beauty of the quaint old resort. Well hidden from the public view and located right in the middle of the forest, surrounded by hills, it was a haven for birders, photographers and nature lovers. The main spot for bird watching and photography was by the side of the dormitory. Multiple birdbaths spaced at irregular intervals and strategically placed branches set the scene for the upcoming show. High-end cameras were set up by the spot. We set up our cameras and went for lunch in <strong>Golghar</strong>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Food</strong> - The lunch was perfect. It catered to people of all tastes. My wife had her share of local veggies, fish and rice. I happily dug into parathas and chicken and did not hesitate to refill my bowl again and again with the yummy local chicken curry.\r\n\r\n<strong>Birding activity</strong> - By the time we reached the main birding spot, there was hardly any place to stand. I refer to it as a <strong>show</strong> because the scene was surreal as if a movie shoot was going on. The attendants refilled the birdbaths at around 3pm. The show had begun by then. The birds started coming one after the other, relentlessly, making way for the others, quenching their thirst, taking dips, arguing, puffing up, hopping about and hardly caring about the photographers. It was a miracle. There goes oriental white eyes, paradise flycatcher, Blythes starling, white-bellied blue flycatcher, rufous woodpecker, <strong>emerald dove</strong>......\r\nBy the end of the day, the birds retreated and we returned back to our cottages with tired fingers and overjoyed hearts. The temperature drops very suddenly after sunset in Ganeshgudi, the altitude being 1800 feet above sea level. To our delight, the attendants called us for a bonfire. We were handed pakodas, steaming hot soups and made to sit around the comforting fire. After a sumptuous dinner in the Golghar, we took a stroll around the resort. We were warned not to venture beyond the gates after dark as there had been numerous sloth bear attacks in the past. The night trail gave us a few significant species  a juvenile tarantula, an unidentified gecko, a tree frog, a scorpion and a <strong>flying squirrel</strong>!\r\nThe next day, we started with the trails around the resort. On our way up a hilly path, we got to see a white bellied woodpecker, which is considered the second largest species of woodpeckers in India, and some other species. The trails around the resort being not so fruitful, we stuck to the main birding area. Not only did several species grace us with their presence, ample photographic opportunities were also provided to us.\r\nIn the afternoon, we took a walk around the Supa dam. The sun was scorching but the breeze from the river cooled us down. We spotted Malabar giant squirrels at every alternate tree. We had to rush back on time for the main birding show. We could not afford to miss that for anything.\r\nOn the third day, we took the same road which led to the dam for the morning trail, the last trail of the trip. The following birds were seen  Orange minivet, flowerpecker, <strong>FILL</strong>.\r\nAfter breakfast we checked out and left the resort to reach Londa for our train.\r\nThe two nights and three days trip went by in a jiffy and we were already looking forward to the next trip. Whew what a trip!!\r\nClick <strong>here</strong> to have a look at the list of birds and other animals.','The Quaint Paradise in Ganeshgudi','','inherit','closed','closed','','66-revision-v1','','','2017-01-18 21:43:26','2017-01-18 16:13:26','',66,'http://amitayu.com/66-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(250,1,'2017-01-19 20:24:02','2017-01-19 14:54:02','Being known by a unique name has its perks. Googling me will let you know that I am the only Amitayu Dey in the entire world. Fun isnt it?\r\nJokes apart, I am a wildlife photographer, an animal lover, a traveler and an avid adventurer. I go on frequent trips across India and sometimes my friends or fellow birders/herpers accompany me.\r\n\r\nFew random things about me:\r\n1. Yes, I am a software engineer by profession and I can still manage to go on frequent nature trips.\r\n2. Animals fascinated me since childhood. The obsession started into a serious passion 6 or 7 years back when I bought my first camera.\r\n3. I do not like to travel with large groups. A small energetic group is appropriate for me.','About','','inherit','closed','closed','','33-revision-v1','','','2017-01-19 20:24:02','2017-01-19 14:54:02','',33,'http://amitayu.com/33-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(253,1,'2017-01-23 14:45:35','2017-01-23 09:15:35','Beautiful Sibia','sibia_namdapha','Beautiful Sibia','inherit','open','closed','','sibia_namdapha','','','2017-01-23 15:11:47','2017-01-23 09:41:47','',92,'http://amitayu.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/sibia_namdapha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(254,1,'2017-01-23 14:45:43','2017-01-23 09:15:43','Green Cochoa','cochoa_namdapha','Green Cochoa','inherit','open','closed','','cochoa_namdapha','','','2017-01-23 15:14:50','2017-01-23 09:44:50','',92,'http://amitayu.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/cochoa_namdapha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(255,1,'2017-01-23 14:45:48','2017-01-23 09:15:48','','forktail_namdapha','','inherit','open','closed','','forktail_namdapha','','','2017-01-23 14:45:48','2017-01-23 09:15:48','',0,'http://amitayu.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/forktail_namdapha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(256,1,'2017-01-23 14:45:53','2017-01-23 09:15:53','White-throated Bulbul','White-throated Bulbul','White-throated Bulbul','inherit','open','closed','','bulbul_namdapha','','','2017-01-30 20:20:12','2017-01-30 14:50:12','',0,'http://amitayu.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/bulbul_namdapha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(257,1,'2017-01-23 14:46:00','2017-01-23 09:16:00','Sultan Tit','sultan_namdapha','Sultan Tit','inherit','open','closed','','sultan_namdapha','','','2017-01-23 15:03:43','2017-01-23 09:33:43','',92,'http://amitayu.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/sultan_namdapha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(258,1,'2017-01-23 14:46:05','2017-